05216nam a22007815i 9780812204124DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132004pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122041247 a10.9783/97808122041242doi  a(DE-B1597)449734  a(OCoLC)979779009  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aREL0400302bisacsh04a296.1/411 aYadin, Azzan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScripture as Logos :bRabbi Ishmael and the Origins of Midrash /cAzzan Yadin. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDivinations: Rereading Late Ancient Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Legal Midrash -- tIntroduction: On the Hermeneutic Dimension of Midrash Halakhah -- tChapter 1. Torah and Ha-Katuv -- tChapter 2. Inaction and Attention -- tChapter 3. Freedom and Restraint in Midrash Halakhah -- tChapter 4. The Role of the Reader I -- tChapter 5. The Role of the Reader II -- tChapter 6. Presponsive Torah -- tChapter 7. Rabbi Ishmael and the Rabbis -- tChapter 8. The Non-Rabbinic Landscape -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe study of midrash—the biblical exegesis, parables, and anecdotes of the Rabbis—has enjoyed a renaissance in recent years. Most recent scholarship, however, has focused on the aggadic or narrative midrash, while halakhic or legal midrash—the exegesis of biblical law—has received relatively little attention. In Scripture as Logos, Azzan Yadin addresses this long-standing need, examining early, tannaitic (70-200 C.E.) legal midrash, focusing on the interpretive tradition associated with the figure of Rabbi Ishmael.This is a sophisticated study of midrashic hermeneutics, growing out of the observation that the Rabbi Ishmael midrashim contain a dual personification of Scripture, which is referred to as both "torah" and "ha-katuv." It is Yadin's significant contribution to note that the two terms are not in fact synonymous but rather serve as metonymies for Sinai on the one hand and, on the other, the rabbinic house of study, the bet midrash. Yadin develops this insight, ultimately presenting the complex but highly coherent interpretive ideology that underlies these rabbinic texts, an ideology that—contrary to the dominant view today—seeks to minimize the role of the rabbinic reader by presenting Scripture as actively self-interpretive.Moving beyond textual analysis, Yadin then locates the Rabbi Ishmael hermeneutic within the religious landscape of Second Temple and post-Temple literature. The result is a series of surprising connections between these rabbinic texts and Wisdom literature, the Dead Sea Scrolls, and the Church Fathers, all of which lead to a radical rethinking of the origins of rabbinic midrash and, indeed, of the Rabbis as a whole.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHalakhic MidrashimxHistory and criticismvTheory, etc. 0aHalakhic MidrashimxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aAncient Studies.  aHistory.  aJewish Studies.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Religionz978311041358808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220412440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812204124423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812204124.jpg  a978